(appendix
  :book             "Book of CS Curriculum"
  :chapter-number   null
  :title            "Appendix H — Constraint satisfaction"
  :prose
"# Appendix H — Constraint satisfaction

The N-queens problem. Sudoku. Map coloring. Scheduling. All the same shape: variables that need values, values that come from domains, constraints that say which combinations are legal.

We build the solver step by step. It uses backtracking + arc consistency. Two hundred lines of Scheme, fifty for the demo.

## The problem shape

```
variables: X1, X2, ..., Xn
domain(Xi): a finite set of values Xi can take
constraints: predicates over subsets of variables
```

Solve = find an assignment `Xi = vi` where every constraint is satisfied.

## The representation

```scheme
(define (make-csp vars doms cons)
  (list 'csp vars doms cons))

(define (csp-vars c) (cadr c))
(define (csp-doms c) (caddr c))
(define (csp-cons c) (cadddr c))
```

Variables and constraints are lists of symbols. Domains map each variable to its allowed values.

## N-queens as a CSP

Four queens: four variables `q1 q2 q3 q4`, one per row. Each domain is `(1 2 3 4)` — column choices. Constraints: no two queens on the same column, no two on a diagonal.

```scheme
(define (nqueens n)
  (make-csp
    (map (lambda (i) (string->symbol (format \"q~a\" i))) (iota n 1))
    (map (lambda (v) (cons v (iota n 1)))
         (map (lambda (i) (string->symbol (format \"q~a\" i))) (iota n 1)))
    (queen-constraints n)))

(define (queen-constraints n)
  (let ((qs (map (lambda (i) (string->symbol (format \"q~a\" i))) (iota n 1))))
    (let loop ((rem qs) (acc '()))
      (if (null? rem) acc
          (loop (cdr rem)
                (append acc
                        (map (lambda (other)
                               (list (car rem) other
                                     (queen-safe-pred (car rem) other)))
                             (cdr rem))))))))
```

Every pair of queens gets a constraint: 'these two must not attack each other.' The predicate:

```scheme
(define (queen-safe-pred qi qj)
  (let ((i (queen-row qi))
        (j (queen-row qj)))
    (lambda (ci cj)
      (and (not (= ci cj))
           (not (= (abs (- ci cj)) (abs (- i j))))))))
```

Different column AND not on the same diagonal (row-difference equals column-difference).

## Backtracking

Try assignments one variable at a time. When a constraint fails, back up.

```scheme
(define (solve csp)
  (let loop ((assignment '()) (remaining (csp-vars csp)))
    (cond ((null? remaining) assignment)
          (else
           (let ((var (car remaining)))
             (let try ((values (domain-of var csp)))
               (cond ((null? values) #f)
                     ((consistent? var (car values) assignment (csp-cons csp))
                      (let ((result (loop (cons (cons var (car values)) assignment)
                                          (cdr remaining))))
                        (if result result (try (cdr values)))))
                     (else (try (cdr values))))))))))
```

Read that inner `try`. Try the first value in the domain. If it's consistent with the assignment so far, recurse. If the recursion succeeds, return the whole solution. If it fails, try the next value. If we exhaust the domain, return `#f` — the assignment can't be extended.

## Consistency

```scheme
(define (consistent? var val assignment constraints)
  (every?
    (lambda (c)
      (cond ((not (or (eq? (car c) var) (eq? (cadr c) var))) #t)
            ((eq? (car c) var)
             (let ((other (assoc (cadr c) assignment)))
               (if other ((caddr c) val (cdr other)) #t)))
            (else
             (let ((other (assoc (car c) assignment)))
               (if other ((caddr c) (cdr other) val) #t)))))
    constraints))
```

For each constraint that mentions our variable, check whether it holds given what's already been assigned. If the other party isn't yet assigned, skip — we'll check when they get their value.

## Try it

```scheme
(solve (nqueens 8))
;=> ((q8 . 5) (q7 . 2) (q6 . 6) (q5 . 1) (q4 . 7) (q3 . 4) (q2 . 8) (q1 . 3))
```

Eight queens on an 8x8 board, no two attacking. Draw it if you like — `q1` is in column 3 of row 1, `q2` in column 8 of row 2, and so on.

## Arc consistency

Backtracking alone is O(k^n). Arc consistency prunes: for each variable, remove domain values that can't possibly satisfy any constraint. Sometimes the propagation makes the problem trivial before backtracking even starts.

The AC-3 algorithm — Alan Mackworth, 1977 — is the classic. Sketch:

```scheme
(define (ac-3 csp)
  (let ((queue (all-arcs csp)))
    (let loop ((q queue) (doms (csp-doms csp)))
      (if (null? q) doms
          (let* ((arc (car q))
                 (revised (revise arc doms)))
            (if (null? (domain-of (car arc) revised))
                'infeasible
                (loop (append (cdr q) (neighbors-arcs (car arc) csp))
                      revised)))))))
```

For each arc `(Xi Xj)`, we ask: for every value in `Xi`'s domain, is there a value in `Xj`'s domain such that the constraint is satisfied? If not, remove that value from `Xi`. If any domain empties, the problem is infeasible.

Combine AC-3 with backtracking and you get MAC (Maintaining Arc Consistency) — reasonably efficient on real-world CSPs.

## Where CSP fits

Sudoku, scheduling, timetabling, register allocation in compilers, protein folding (approximated), circuit layout, resource allocation. Anywhere the problem is 'assign values to variables under constraints,' CSP is a candidate.

## The reasoning limits show up here

CSP is a place where Scheme's power is at its cleanest — the code IS the reasoner. Every variable is symbolic, every constraint is a predicate you write, every solution is a proof.

The place it stops being clean: when the constraints are soft (some are preferences, not requirements) or fuzzy (this photo 'is more of a cat' than that one). Then you need weighted CSP or fuzzy CSP or optimization, and you're back on the negotiation side of the reasoning-limits story. See Appendix D.

## For further reading

Russell & Norvig, *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach*, chapter on constraint satisfaction. Mackworth's original AC-3 paper. Prolog is a language whose evaluator IS a CSP solver with unification — see the mini-Prolog project in the 25-projects list.
")
